Inflation in Europe has fallen on food
The acceleration of inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the steep increase in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 eurozone countries, with annual inflation of 3.1% after 2.6 per cent in October, the European Union’s Statistical Office in Luxembourg reported.
The official forecast was only 3% likely, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the base rate, saying that the cut, along with rising commodity prices and lessening unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep inflation rates below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is trapped in its twenty-two trap: “Turn off inflation” so that it does not have to act on this issue later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent in November was a record for twelve years; in Spain, it rose from 4.1 to 3.6.
Eurozone inflation was driven by rising food and energy prices.
Wheat quotes have risen by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached their highest level since 1973.
Eating oil and dairy products also had to pay significantly more in 2007.
World oil prices have risen by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost nearly <0x24>100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% over the next three to four months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to have fallen interest rates twice in 2008.
