The most expensive is Auchan, raised by almost a fifth by Tesco
In the trade triangle in Budaörs, the hypermarkets maintained an average price increase of 16% last year, with the difference that VAT did not increase this year.
The Daily Economy Article
This year, on average, the usual Christmas basket of the Day grew by 16 percent in the Budaörs trade triangle, but in each hypermarket there was an increase in value well above a thousand forints.
As the prices in grocery stores have already “slipped” in December last year, there was no drastic increase in the percentage compared to the previous high base.
But it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they got last year for just nine thousand forints, now they can’t even get it for ten thousand.
The Daily basket in the hypermarkets examined exceeded the psychological limit of 10,000 HUF by at least 91 forints.
The highest basket value was HUF 10,573.
(In 2003, the basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as last year, but turkey breast fillets, walnuts and poppy seeds were also very expensive.
The prices of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH, although we found a kilogram of bread in Auchan for 139 forints.
The competition did not push the price of the product below 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the two-liter returnable bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so they asked for only 257 forints for the product, including the deposit fee.
This year, however, the Auchan was the most expensive in the Daily basket, while the Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased the prices in the Daily Cart by about 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan increased the prices in the Daily Cart by about 18 to 18 percent.
Compared to last year’s most expensive and this year’s cheapest basket value, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive was 21 percent.
The average increase in forints was 1480.
Last year, the average price increase came to HUF 1,206, so that last Christmas the increase in VAT made its impact felt in the prices.
It was precisely this process that disrupted trade, and the stores were apparently unable to decide how much margin they would apply to each product, as they were unable to calculate the effect of price changes on consumption.
(If the speed of rotation of a product is badly planned by the trader, it can benefit greatly from a margin adjusted for traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the price increase of the Daily basket was so extreme last year that the most expensive one was HUF 1,720 more than in 2006, while the cheapest one had a price difference of only HUF 844.
This extreme did not show up this year, as the most expensive one was 1,630 forints more than last year, and the cheapest one was 1,284 forints more expensive.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, there was a disastrous price increase, with daily consumer goods in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This does not necessarily confirm the data of the HCSO: for some basic foodstuffs, the statistical office recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent over a 12-month period.
In addition to eggs, for example.)
