Savings on disinfectants in many places
More than 1,000 infections have been reported in hospitals this year, mainly due to the inadequate use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions of the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overload of staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the head of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many places, they also save on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
A bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a man after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the beginning of the year.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but had to return with MRSA shortly afterwards, and an important surgery could not be performed because of the bacteria in his body.
1094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System by 10 December this year, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that infections caused by so many multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, the rest is not known.
Approximately two-thirds (683 infections) of the infections are caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. pharyngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are well curable.
However, when antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into highly resistant bacteria that spread quickly in poor hospital conditions.
In particular, when the immune system is temporarily or permanently impaired, it can cause serious hospital infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis - in patients with a weak body, elderly or low weight.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, only MRSA is not there, said Tibor Kanulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistant to antibiotics
“We isolate such patients, the nursing staff supplies them with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Kanulasi.
Patients who are admitted to the hospital are tested for the presence of MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
There is no sampling
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current Hungarian hospital conditions and conditions are not favourable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection typically occurs in hospitals, elderly homes, hospitals should monitor patients entering and isolate patients carrying MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It is also important that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies.
Most of the cases are revealed when a patient has a detectable MRSA infection, the head of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of resistance to drugs, but this is not always the case in hospitals.
Microbiological samples are even rarer in outpatient and primary care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Save on disinfectants
There is scientific evidence that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another through the mediation of medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant deficiencies in this in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet infection and contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate an infected patient.
In fact, the hospital rooms are often crowded, often very close to each other, although epidemiologically patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina Böröcz noted that hospitals in a financially unfavourable situation save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, so the chances of developing infections are even higher.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, less such infection can be detected or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treating an MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurers, so it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government included prevention and reduction of MRSA in its programme.
The program appears to be successful, with MRSA infections showing a decreasing trend in England, according to the reported data.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) prioritises the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
