Fodor and the six percent of Hungarians
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the expert meetings will be concluded on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the talks with the ministers will continue with the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts to follow the emission reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
There is currently a heated debate on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not want to negotiate precise figures at the moment, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether developed countries will commit themselves not only to reducing emissions, but also to providing both financial and technological assistance to those countries that need it.
There is also an agreement on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, as provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, which is expected to be part of the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), according to Market and Profit.
6% of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to preserve its flagship role in global climate protection efforts and to promote the establishment of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU would undertake to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the "post-2012 agreement", and was ready to commit to a reduction of up to 30 per cent if other major developed regions of the world and developing countries were willing to undertake commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997, the countries that acceded to the Kyoto Protocol set a target of a reduction of 5.2 per cent, including the EU – then the 15 Member States – committed to a reduction of minus 8 per cent.
The obligation for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the period 1985-87, which Hungary will fulfill, the Ministry of the Environment’s press release recalls.
The stakes are high in Bali, as the long-term international climate agreement has to be concluded within two years, otherwise its entry into force would definitely be postponed beyond 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol’s reduction commitments would not be immediately followed by another international emission reduction scheme, which the IPCC, the latest UN Nobel Peace Prize-winning international scientific body on climate change, pointed out in its latest report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and make it inevitable that the global average temperature will rise above 2 degrees Celsius, with extremely serious and irreversible consequences, according to scientists.
