Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the country’s risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division.
The company’s “risk warning” said that the biggest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that “with the escalation of the ethnic tensions that already exist between the gypsy and non-gypsy populations in Hungary, even violent ethnic clashes may develop in the short term”.
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is probably aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this is due to one of the main failures of Hungarian political actors: “the public discussion of the Roma issue was allowed by public actors to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Gypsy-Hungarian antagonism.”
This deepens the problem, renders normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, as a result of the great national and international media attention, “degraded the image of Hungary abroad significantly, especially in terms of belief in the stability and democratic development of the country”.
It is recalled that as part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which gained more and more publicity and momentum from the autumn of 2006, several associations called “national self-defence” were formed in Hungary from the summer of 2007.
“The common feature of these associations is that they define themselves as a civil society organisation, while openly promoting the preparation of their members – even armed – for defence (catastrophe protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, in addition to the incompetence of the police, the army, i.e. the state,” they added.
They noted that this is done in accordance with the method which, based on the anti-political and anti-partisan attitude of society, seeks to put various political aspirations into the civilian cloak.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association are therefore not only used to avoid legal pitfalls of court registration in the case of these associations, but are also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are a risk-increasing factor from the point of view of neighbourhood relations.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring states, and the ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
This affects the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
As they wrote, the operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, for example, the establishment of which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The formation of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of the districts of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this to decide to establish a guard, saying that the organization’s goal was “national self-defense.”
