After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive, which documented the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime, became public.
The 47 million archived documents, which occupy 27 kilometres of shelving in Bad Arolsen in the Hesse region, could only be searched for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. they only provided unique and name-based access for the victims of the past or their descendants.
