Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making the documents public, as they contained names and therefore confidential information.
This could be, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were collected after the war for practical reasons, with the aim of searching for deported or forced labour civilians and possibly providing evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently engaged in the processing of tens of thousands of individual needs.
