Congress approves adoption of MiFID, which entered into force on 1 November
Parallel to the parliamentary process, which ended today with a congressional vote approving the Senate’s amendments, the government initiated a social dialogue on the underlying legislation so that both could enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts of the MEPs and Senators in negotiating and concluding agreements aimed at establishing the most favourable legal framework for the protection of investors, as well as the detailed regulation of the activities of companies, in order to ensure efficient market operation.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, will allow for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, expanding the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new Directive will allow financial advisory services for specialised companies, but also for natural or legal persons, and create a new form of financial services company (ESIS), namely financial advisory firms (AFIs), in addition to securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the Act increases the number of systems capable of executing transactions involving funds, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and internalization systems executing orders that compete with current stock market participants.
Furthermore, the Act obliges investment service providers to provide market information on the defining aspects of their business profile, risk-taking and risk management, and to keep records of all transactions carried out in order to facilitate the control of CNMV.
The Congressional Economic Commission has filed a number of amendments. Among these, it is of the utmost importance that securitised debts are treated as "complex" funds, due to the high risk to investors. This has been proven in connection with US high-risk mortgage lending (subprime).
