What kind of insurance suits me?
Car insurance, which means security for the owner of the car against various damages, involves a significant expense and depends on several factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured and nature of use.
Buying a car is just the first step.
In fact, choosing the right insurance is often more difficult than deciding what type of car you want.
First of all, we need to be clear about what this is all about.
Car insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insured.
This agreement takes the form of an insurance contract stating that the insurance company undertakes to compensate against a fixed premium in the event of the occurrence of the damage.
In practice, the premium is the amount paid for insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors such as age, gender, date of obtaining the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured, its use, and more.
Insurance companies calculate the premium on the basis of statistics, i.e. those who have a higher risk of accidents pay a higher amount.
That’s why people over the age of 25, or women, pay less, because statistics show that they are less risky because they are more cautious.
Similarly, insurance companies have concluded that married people cause fewer accidents than lonely people.
Frequency is crucial for the type of car used.
With more frequent use, the possibility of an accident increases.
Many factors are taken into account by insurance companies when determining the premium.
Therefore, the owner should look carefully to choose the most suitable form of insurance for his profile.
In the following, we present the most important factors in the choice, so that you can best adapt to the needs of the insured and create an acceptable price.
When concluding an insurance contract, people under the age of 25 will have to face a number of drawbacks, such as lack of driving experience and freshness of the driving license.
Although it is ideal to be insured against all dangers, there are also more economical solutions.
More cautious drivers can take out full insurance on their own, so they will be insured against all dangers and the price will be affordable.
In this type of contract, the insured pays part of the damage.
“The amount of self-sufficiency that an insured person must pay depends on the insurance premium; the higher the premium, the lower the self-sufficiency,” says Luis Noguera, head of First Europa, an online insurance broker in Spain.
Another option is third party liability insurance, where the customer insures himself against damage to others, but not against damage to his own car.
In addition, it will be insured against theft, fire damage and loss of the car.
Here's some advice.
If you are under the age of 25, be careful and avoid accidents, as this will affect the bonus and you can reduce the amount you pay in the future.
Bonuses are defined as discounts granted compared to the basic tariff of the insurance company.
The penalty imposed compared to the basic tariff is called malus.
The amount of bonus and malus depends on the insurance company and its profits.
If the company has had a good year, you can afford to increase the bonus rate,” explains Noguera.
Once the age of 25 has been exceeded, it is easier for owners to take out appropriate insurance, as the risk of accidents is reduced thanks to the experience gained over the years.
We recommend that you take out a full insurance policy.
"In general, young people are not yet able to properly apply their experience in an accident, or even when driving," says the Spanish director of the European insurance company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, when drivers have already gone beyond the fear of beginners.
If the insured person is already married but does not yet have children, it is best to take out a full insurance policy, of course, provided that his or her financial possibilities allow it.
Insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the least risky customers, so in their case, the fee to be paid is also lower.
In this case, it is best to have full insurance with part of yourself (this can reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>300), or if you have a higher bonus, you can extend the insurance from the third year of the car to cover damage caused to others.
"They drive more calmly, but at the same time they have greater purchasing power and can afford to have a higher share of themselves," says Luis Noguera.
In the case of pensioners, we recommend full insurance with a part of yourself (which is around 150 euros) or, in case of a higher bonus, it can be extended to liability insurance.
Car insurance is a very important thing, not only because it provides protection for the owner in the event of damage, but also because it represents a high cost, so it is essential to choose the right form of personalized insurance.
