The Scottish NHS committees need to improve the control of criminal records of workers from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal was brought forward by chief accountant Robert Black after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to an attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Mr Black also expressed concern that the NHS Scotland does not have accurate data on the number of its overseas employees.
At the same time, his report, through a sample of five health authorities, also pointed out key checks that were properly carried out.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the chief auditor checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
28-year-old Bilal Abdullah, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep hit the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors charged with attempted car bombings in the United Kingdom in October via video contact with the Old Bailey court.
In the case of their employees from overseas countries, the NHS committees must verify the qualifications and work experience of the workers concerned and their availability of the necessary permits to work in the United Kingdom before they take up employment.
Although Scottish health committees use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not entitled to obtain such information from outside the UK.
The report of the Chief Auditor suggested, among other things, that the committees should introduce a guide to the Criminal Records Office, which would facilitate the verification process for employers with different overseas countries.
"While we have found evidence of such checks in the records of staff, they are not being carried out regularly," the report said.
According to Black, while the Scottish NHS is performing its own pre-employment screening process at a high level, he added: “Our report highlights areas of the system that can be improved in order to keep up-to-date information on the number of NHS staff from overseas.”
Dr. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was “extremely unlikely” that pre-employment checks could help us identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"According to the report, the current pre-employment checks are working well in the NHS Scotland, and the value of the proposals made is not yet transparent," he said.
According to Scottish health authorities, their current number of overseas employees, mostly doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the main auditor pointed out that the figures were likely to be higher, partly because the committees had problems identifying staff on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the inspection procedures put in place in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and the NHS authorities in Lothian operate to a large extent in a coordinated manner.
These procedures included the verification of passports, work permits and evidence of professional qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently examining a directive and guidance on pre-employment checks for NHS employees from overseas countries.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was delighted that this task was carried out after the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, will take into account the recommendations in the report and ensure that the updated guide on pre-employment checks for the entire staff, including those from overseas, reflects best practice. An updated version is planned to be published next month.
