Venus is the evil twin of Earth.
Despite its harsh atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously assumed: In its atmosphere, the European spacecraft Venus Express has detected lightning strikes and wind turbulences in its polar orbits, such as those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that it is lightning on Venus.
The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has provided evidence - electromagnetic waves have been detected at the periphery of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at an altitude of approximately 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, on the columns of the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "early soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was triggered by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in the very early days," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington, D.C.
At present, there can hardly be a living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is roughly a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the hellish twin of Earth, but it's still her twin," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different path of evolution.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus exploration because since the early 1990s, no probe has been on its way specifically to this planet.
The latest findings, already presented in several "Nature" articles, are not only proof of the uniqueness of Venus within the Solar System.
"They also suggest that the neighboring planet has a greater resemblance to Earth than we initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the known Arctic whirlwind, researchers have also discovered an even faster-moving cloud vortex in the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, according to a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The solar system's second innermost planet has almost the same mass as Earth, and its 12,100-kilometre diameter is almost the same size as Earth.
The star, also known as the Morning Star, orbits the Sun in less than 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus’ surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius, coupled with a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets originated under exactly the same conditions.
Both had water accumulate, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while on Venus it left for the universe.
And while on Earth carbon dioxide is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus it forms a large part of the atmosphere.
