After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, the internal investigation of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has come to a sobering conclusion: The Pontus Hultén, a large part of the "Brillo Box" given to Moderna Museet in 1995.
The prehistory is a long and complicated chain of artistic and curatorial stunts.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York - painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of "Brillo" soap powder.
At an exhibition held at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of Brillo boxes were exhibited: These were not (for cost-saving reasons) from Warhol, but were shipped directly from the Brillo carton factory.
It wasn’t about artworks, it was about their templates, simple exhibits.
However, in 1968, Warhol granted permission to produce a few Brillo wallads in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the time now speak of about fifteen boxes that rightly entered the history of art and auctions under the designation of "Stockholm-type" as the then certified Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box.
Some of them were auctioned for over <0x24>100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred wooden boxes were manufactured and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were only manufactured in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, however, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the main museum administrator at Moderna Museet, inspected the museum’s six Brillo Boxes, as well as three Swedish privately owned boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed chipboards were first flattened and sanded down, and the white oil paint was then applied with a brush.
The structure of the replicas from 1990, on the other hand, indicates that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a dye roller, without any foundation – and it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not certified by the artist, so they should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "Unless the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
The Authentication Board, of course, announced in June that it was investigating “serious accusations” about soap dust boxes.
Since then, however, they have been enclosed in unrelenting silence.
